    41â†’/* The Upstream request is the base class for forwarding HTTP upstream.
    42â†’ *
    43â†’ * On the new request path, payload (headers/body/metadata/data) still arrives via
    44â†’ * the accept[X]fromRouter functions. Said data is immediately passed off to the
    45â†’ * UpstreamFilterManager, which passes each item through the filter chain until
    46â†’ * it arrives at the last filter in the chain, the UpstreamCodecFilter. If the upstream
    47â†’ * stream is not established, the UpstreamCodecFilter returns StopAllIteration, and the
    48â†’ * FilterManager will buffer data, using watermarks to push back to the router
    49â†’ * filter if buffers become overrun. When an upstream connection is established,
    50â†’ * the UpstreamCodecFilter will send data upstream.
    51â†’ *
    52â†’ * On the new response path, payload arrives from upstream via the UpstreamCodecFilter's
    53â†’ * CodecBridge. It is passed off directly to the FilterManager, traverses the
    54â†’ * filter chain, and completion is signaled via the
    55â†’ * UpstreamRequestFilterManagerCallbacks's encode[X] functions. These somewhat
    56â†’ * confusingly pass through the UpstreamRequest's legacy decode[X] functions
    57â†’ * (required due to the UpstreamToDownstream interface, but will be renamed once
    58â†’ * the classic mode is deprecated), and are finally passed to the router via the
    59â†’ * RouterFilterInterface onUpstream[X] functions.
    60â†’ *
    61â†’ * There is some required communication between the UpstreamRequest and
    62â†’ * UpstreamCodecFilter. This is accomplished via the UpstreamStreamFilterCallbacks
    63â†’ * interface, with the UpstreamFilterManager acting as intermediary.
    64â†’ *
    65â†’ */
